<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="32" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="32">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="32">
This genus includes 79 species in the world (
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="32">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
), and many of these are grass-living. In Iran, only 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips obscurus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">Anaphothrips obscurus</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="MÃ¼ller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips sudanensis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudanensis">Anaphothrips sudanensis</taxonomicName>
Trybom have been reported (
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="32">Bhatti et al. 2009a</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, the male of the widely distributed species 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Anaphothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anaphothrips obscurus" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">Anaphothrips obscurus</taxonomicName>
is described only from Iran (
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="65 - 68" title="First description of the male of the wheat thrips, Anaphothrips obscurus (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." volume="2540" year="2010 b">Mirab-balou and Chen 2010b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
